equation_narrative.headline: Charged local context drives Q prediction despite hydrophobic early representation
equation_narrative.story: Position 28 sits in a charged local environment (IENVK[A]KIQDK) that dominates the model's perception. Early layers (1-9) assemble a hydrophobic-leaning representation, with L peaking at 42.8% at L9 and A reaching 21.3%, reflecting generic small-residue encoding before structural context arrives. The perception phase (L10-23) is turbulent, with 13 lead changes as the model integrates conflicting signals: 5 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions. The decision phase (L24-33) resolves toward Q, driven by strong polar/charged prediction channels at L29-30 (F30:6682, F30:2619) and decisive MLP neurons (N29:2875, N29:1110) that push A to 30.4% at L29 before Q overtakes at L30, reaching 40.7% by L33.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-9 build a generic hydrophobic representation, with L dominating the logit lens (42.8% at L9) and A rising to 21.3%, reflecting early features that encode small, non-polar residue character (F9:5728, F9:1281, F9:2619 all project 54-64). This is NOT a prediction—it's the model encoding local sequence statistics before structural information arrives. Layers 10-23 are marked by extreme instability (13 lead changes) as structural contacts and co-evolutionary signals flow in. Attention heads at L12 (head 1, +2.5 proj) and L17 (head 1, -1.98 proj) drive major shifts. By L18, the representation character shifts toward polar/charged residues (S, R, A oscillate in the logit lens), consistent with the charged local context (K27, K29, D32). Features at L18 (F18:6256, F18:5712) encode this contextual polarity. The representation at L23 shows A at 18.6%, S at 20.6%, reflecting a context that is surface-exposed and charge-adjacent rather than buried hydrophobic.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the model has assembled a representation consistent with a surface-exposed position in a charged local environment (flanked by K27, K29, D32). The 5 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions contribute conflicting signals, but the immediate sequence context dominates, creating a polar/charged-leaning representation.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 5 residues within 8Å, read primarily at L12 (head 1, +2.5 proj) and L17 (head 1, -1.98 proj)
Co-evolutionary coupling: 2 positions provide weak signal, insufficient to override local context
L9 features: F9:5728 (63.9 proj), F9:1281 (58.7 proj) encode hydrophobic/small-residue character before structural integration
L18 features: F18:6256 (20.8 proj), F18:5712 (19.7 proj) encode polar/charged context after structural information arrives

decision_phase.summary: The transition to decision begins at L24, where MLP neurons first cast strong amino-acid-specific votes (N24:589 votes K>R>A, N24:111 votes N>A>G). Q emerges as a serious contender at L29-30, driven by high-enrichment prediction features (F30:6682, F30:2619, F30:5728 all project 51-55) and decisive MLP neurons (N29:2875 pushes A with +0.79 proj, N29:1110 pushes S/K/A with +0.58 proj). A peaks at 30.4% at L29 but collapses to 5.8% by L33 as Q surges from 25.8% to 40.7%, powered by attention at L32 (head 15, +3.3 proj) and massive MLP support at L32 (N32:3989 with +1.63 proj toward A, but net MLP push of +2.81 favors Q).
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to decision. At L23, the logit lens shows S (20.6%) and A (18.6%) reflecting representation character. At L24, MLP neurons (N24:589, N24:111) activate with amino-acid-specific votes, and A jumps to 28.7%. This is the first layer where the probabilities reflect actual prediction rather than representation character—AA-specific prediction channels are now online.

candidates.narrative: Q emerges decisively in the decision phase, rising from 7.8% at L23 to 25.8% at L29 and peaking at 56.4% at L32 before settling at 40.7%. The surge is driven by high-enrichment prediction features at L30 (F30:6682, F30:2619, F30:5728 project 51-55) and powerful MLP support at L29-32. N29:1110 (+0.58 proj) votes S/K/A but the net MLP activity at L29 (+1.6 total) and L32 (+2.81 total) strongly favors Q. Attention head 15 at L32 (+3.3 proj) provides the final push, reading structural contacts to confirm Q as the polar residue best suited to this charged environment.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L29, dominant by L30, peaks L32
key_evidence: F30:2619 (MLP, 54.7 proj) — polar residue prediction feature
N32:3989 (MLP, +1.63 proj) — massive A-writer but net MLP favors Q
L32 head 15 (attn, +3.3 proj) — structural writer confirming Q

candidates.narrative: K is a consistent contender throughout the decision phase, peaking at 18.2% at L25 and finishing at 17.0%. It's supported by the charged local context (K27, K29 flanking) and receives votes from MLP neurons that favor charged residues (N24:589 votes K>R>A with +0.25 proj). However, K lacks the strong prediction channel support that Q receives at L29-30, and it never gains decisive momentum. The model appears to favor Q's polar amide over K's positive charge for this specific context.
key_evidence: Charged local context (K27, K29) supports K but insufficient to win

candidates.narrative: L dominates the logit lens in early layers, peaking at 42.8% at L9, but this reflects the hydrophobic character of the representation before structural context arrives—NOT a model prediction. Features at L9 (F9:5728, F9:1281) encode generic small/hydrophobic residue properties. As structural contacts and local sequence context integrate (L10-17), L collapses from 42.8% to 5.2%, erased by attention heads that read the charged environment (L12 head 1, L17 head 1). By the decision phase, L is irrelevant (9.3% final), as the model has fully incorporated the polar/charged context.
key_evidence: F9:5728 (attn, 63.9 proj) — hydrophobic encoding before context
L12 head 1 (+2.5 proj) — structural reading erases L
L17 head 1 (-1.98 proj) — further erasure as charged context dominates

candidates.narrative: A is the true residue but finishes 5th (5.8%). It shows strength in the perception phase, rising from 20.0% at L0 to 30.4% at L29, supported by features encoding small, flexible residues in charged contexts (F18:6256, F24:10131). A receives massive MLP support at L29 (N29:2875 +0.79 proj, N29:825 +0.50 proj) and L32 (N32:3989 +1.63 proj, N32:2629 +1.27 proj). However, A collapses from 30.4% to 5.8% between L29 and L33, erased by attention heads at L30 (head 7, -2.4 proj) and L32 (head 19, -1.7 proj) that favor Q's polar character over A's hydrophobic simplicity.
key_evidence: L30 head 7 (attn, -2.4 proj) — structural eraser favoring Q
L32 head 19 (attn, -1.7 proj) — final erasure of A

candidates.narrative: E is a minor contender, rising from 0.4% at L0 to 7.9% at L33, consistent with the charged local context. It receives support from features encoding negative charge (F30:2619 also supports E) but never gains strong MLP backing. E peaks at 9.2% at L27 and remains stable through the decision phase, suggesting the model considers it plausible but inferior to Q's polar amide for this specific environment.
key_evidence: F30:2619 (MLP, 54.7 proj) — supports polar/charged residues including E

turning_points.description: The hydrophobic early representation collapses as structural information arrives. L drops from 42.8% to 22.5%, and A drops from 21.3% to 17.8%. Attention head 1 at L12 (+2.5 proj) reads local sequence context, integrating the charged environment (K27, K29, D32). MLP neurons at L10-12 erase hydrophobic candidates (N10:3298 -0.41 proj, N12:285 -0.23 proj) and begin writing polar/charged character. This is the transition from generic sequence encoding to context-aware representation.

The perception-to-decision transition. At L23, the logit lens shows S (20.6%) and A (18.6%), reflecting a polar/charged representation. At L24, MLP neurons activate with amino-acid-specific votes (N24:589 votes K>R>A, N24:111 votes N>A>G), and A jumps to 28.7%. This is the first layer where probabilities reflect actual prediction rather than representation character. The model has shifted from 'what is this context' to 'what amino acid fits this context.'

The decisive Q surge. A peaks at 30.4% at L29, supported by massive MLP writers (N29:2875 +0.79 proj, N29:825 +0.50 proj). But at L30, Q overtakes A (38.8% vs 30.4%), driven by high-enrichment prediction features (F30:6682, F30:2619, F30:5728) and attention erasure of A (L30 head 7, -2.4 proj). At L32, Q peaks at 56.4% as MLP neurons deliver +2.81 net projection and attention head 15 (+3.3 proj) confirms Q by reading structural contacts. A collapses to 5.8% by L33, erased by attention heads that favor Q's polar character.

deep_dives.label: Early hydrophobic features (L1, L9)
deep_dives.caption: These features encode generic hydrophobic/small-residue character before structural context arrives. High projections (54-64) reflect representation character, not prediction. Watch them collapse as structural information integrates at L10-17.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention (L12, L17)
deep_dives.caption: L12 head 1 (+2.5 proj) reads local charged context, erasing hydrophobic candidates. L17 head 1 (-1.98 proj) continues this erasure. These heads integrate the 5 structural contacts and shift the representation from hydrophobic to polar/charged.

deep_dives.label: Context encoding (L18)
deep_dives.caption: Features at L18 encode the polar/charged context after structural integration. F18:6256 (20.8 proj) and F18:5712 (19.7 proj) reflect the model's understanding that this position is surface-exposed and charge-adjacent.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset (L24)
deep_dives.caption: First layer where MLP neurons cast amino-acid-specific votes. N24:589 votes K>R>A, N24:111 votes N>A>G. This is the transition from representation to prediction—probabilities now reflect actual model beliefs.

deep_dives.label: Q prediction channels (L30)
deep_dives.caption: High-enrichment features that activate specifically for Q. F30:6682 (55.4 proj), F30:2619 (54.7 proj), and F30:5728 (53.9 proj) are the primary prediction channels driving Q's surge from 25.8% to 38.8% at L30.

deep_dives.label: A peak and collapse (L29-32)
deep_dives.caption: N29:2875 (+0.79 proj) and N29:825 (+0.50 proj) push A to 30.4% at L29. But N32:3989 (+1.63 proj) and N32:2629 (+1.27 proj) write A while net MLP activity (+2.81) favors Q. Watch the competition between A-writers and Q-supporting neurons.

deep_dives.label: Final decision (L30-32)
deep_dives.caption: L30 head 7 (-2.4 proj) erases A, L32 head 15 (+3.3 proj) confirms Q by reading structural contacts, and L32 head 19 (-1.7 proj) provides final A erasure. These heads resolve the A vs Q competition in favor of Q.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model assembles a representation of position 28 as surface-exposed and charge-adjacent, flanked by K27, K29, and D32. This context drives the decision toward polar/charged residues, with Q winning over K and A. The strongest evidence is the convergence of high-enrichment prediction features at L30 (F30:6682, F30:2619, F30:5728) and decisive MLP support at L29-32 (net +2.81 proj at L32). The model predicts Q (40.7%) instead of the correct A (5.8%) because it overweights the charged local context and underweights A's small, flexible character—A receives massive MLP support (N32:3989 +1.63 proj) but is erased by attention heads that favor Q's polar amide for this charged environment.
